{"key":"processedPost-9834629","value":{"id":9834629,"first":8270900,"last":19759819,"when":1235174268,"utime":"02/21/09 01:57 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />Go to Home Depot, Lowes, or any small hardware store and go pick up a fat bag of Plaster Of Paris <br /></blockquote><br /><br />If you do that, mix it with water, allow it to set up, and then break it up with a hammer.&nbsp; It's best not to use it in powder form right out of the bag.&nbsp; It does the opposite of what you want.<br /><br />You don't need to get too anal about removing the paper from drywall.&nbsp; The garden gypsum I get comes from the broken scraps at a drywall plant and is full of paper.&nbsp; The mycelium eats it right up.&nbsp; You also don't need to smash it to a fine powder, because as soon as it gets damp in your substrate or casing layer mix, it falls apart.<br />RR","title":"Re: Can you use crushed drywall as gypsum??","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}